description.text:
Remixed from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:51489 (user 271828 - thanks!)

This modified spindle has the string hole removed for strength, and is extended down to just above the base, with a tapered hole for motor cog. I used an old Honeybee CP2 helicopter brushed motor, which surprisingly has plenty enough torque to launch the blades 30+ meters. This would be lethal with a more suitable motor that is designed for direct drive as in this application (low Kv/rpm , more torque).

Motor was attached by adding some screws to it's in-built mounting holes but not screwing them up, then heating the motor with a heat gun and melting it into the end of the handle. The screws melt the plastic and slide up into the slot on the bottom of the handle for a solid mounting. The cog melts into the tapered hole of the spindle.

title: Modified prusa i3 x-carriage with Laser support

description.text:
See a full description of the project on Sway: https://sway.com/LqQa1e8HWW4ZqbUk

I added a J Tech 2.8 Watt Laser Diode to a Sintron Prusa I3.

You may find that mounting the Laser 100 MM above the print bed does not allow as fine a laser as you would like. Optimal is 30 MM, but I wanted to mount the Laser higher and allow both laser and 3D printer to work potentially in conjunction.

I planned on moving the level sensor to the back of the x-carriage to be more centrally located in the x-y plane to measure the z-axis limit. I have designed a new sensor mount for that purpose which is also attached. Also note that moving the Z-position sensor to the back of the carriage can limit the Z- movement by some amount - depending on your your printer's frame. In my case that was about 15 MM of Z travel that I lost from the top end. It could also affect X-axis travel, again depending on your printer's frame.

Last added picture shows laser cut gear made on 1/8 inch thick Bassword. This took 4 passes at the 2 AMP setting at 50% speed and 1 pass at full speed.

The following steps are my build process:

  1. Purchase Laser Diode and controller from JTech (http://jtechphotonics.com/?page_id=1503)

  2. Design and print x-carriage to support laser diode and MK8 extruder. I used PET + filament. Stuff works really well in my opinion.

  3. Wire laser diode controller into Ramps 1.4 Fan output on D9

  4. Mount new carriage with Laser diode and MK8 extruder.

  5. Adjust Laser diode focus using lowest amperage setting.

  6. Determine proper x-y offsets for gcode based on laser diode offset from extruder print head.

  7. Get some sample SVG files to laser engrave/cut using InckScape and the gcode plugin to output the gcode file.

description.text: A 4 position geneva gear. It include a small assembly to hold the gears. 3 total parts.

My house has a timber deck out back with some small LED deck lights. Some of the lights have failed or broken, and they are quite expensive to replace and painful to fix. I designed and printed a replacement part using translucent ABS. It is sized to fit in the same 20mm hole, and uses 3 x Blue LEDs and a 100ohm resistor is series for a 12VDC supply. I coated the finished product with outdoor clear varnish which hopefully will provide some UV protection.

The third photo shows the printed version vs the original (which has the metal surround).

The design on the light is in the OpenSCAD file attached. There are 3 holes sized for a snug fit of standard 5mm LEDs. It's better to assemble and solder up the LEDs separately (I used a cut up test print as a template/holder). Then they can be carefully pushed in place and the end filled with silicon sealant.

The design on the light is in the OpenSCAD file attached. There are 3 holes sized for a snug fit of standard 5mm LEDs. It's better to assemble and solder up the LEDs separately (I used a cut up test print as a template/holder). Then they can be carefully pushed in place and the end filled with silicon sealant.

The OpenSCAD design can be tailored for different sizes and profiles. The "burrs" help keep the light in the timber hole without having to use glue.

I printed using clear ABS on a Migbot Reprap with 1.2 walls and 0.1mm layer height. I used a brim for adhesion and cleaned up the edges with a dremel tool.

The deck lights go into a 20mm diameter hole in the timber decking - the wiring is hidden underneath. A purist may want to indent the top square by a millimeter or so. I haven't bothered since the lights are placed near the walls (not in an area where someone will kick them).

comments.text: If you have a chance, could you please take a picture of how you light mounts outside. And what it looks like with the lights on.
comments.author: pvtkirsch

comments.text: Done.  The lights just go into a 20mm hole in the timber decking.  The wiring is hidden underneath.  In my case the lights are close to the walls - in areas where people are unlikely to step on them.  If they are in heavy traffic areas then the top square can be indented into the timber and possible made thicker.

This is a wrench to help open and close plastic soda bottles. I developed it for my mother-in-law who has arthritis in her thumb joints and has difficulty with unscrewing these bottle caps by hand.
I experimented with several concepts before hitting on the opposed teeth that you see here. The idea is that the teeth will flex when the wrench is pushed onto the cap. When the wrench is turned, one of the sets of three teeth will bend upward and grip the cap surface.
This particular design is a compromise between ease of pushing on (it still takes a good push) and strength of grip. If anyone makes one, I would like to know how well it works for them.

Once printed, you may need to clean up the tips of the teeth to make sure it will push on to a cap smoothly.
It will work from either side.
Press it down over the cap so it stays. You can unscrew the cap and leave the wrench on for when you need to screw the cap back onto the bottle.

description.text: This design is part of a project to build a children's climbing harness. But in and of itself can be used in countless different ways. This is simply a prototype, and is not designed to be load bearing. Take it as a proof of concept. First of all let me say that no force tests have been accomplished on this device for the purpose of climbing as of yet. And, even when I do publish the results of the stress tests, it will be entirely dependent on the quality of your machine, and materials as to whether or not they have the same performance. So use this for climbing applications at your own risk.

Tie the smooth side of the buckles together using a butterfly or water knot(or sew with high strength thread if you've got it). Ensure when arranging the pieces that the small buckle faces outward.
Take the other end of the 1 inch webbing and insert it first through the main opening in both buckle components.
Follow the webbing over the top buckle, and under the bottom buckle.
Pull until comfortably tight, and admire its simple beauty.

comments.text: yes, this is just a cute design that can show how actual ones work, anything rated above 20kn is common as it will only take 7-9 kn across the gate such as in a simple D carabiner
comments.author: cb2printer

comments.text: I like your buckle design and think it would be great for a belt or backpack strap (or maybe even a low hanging slack line) but under no condition would I even think of using a printed buckle on a climbing harness.  I don't believe that these printers are anywhere near consistent enough to say "this buckle broke at 50 lbs so every buckle will break at 50 lbs".  Sure you could test a thousand of them but would you take a drug that killed every 1/1000 people?
comments.author: ftc

comments.text: I like the idea of trying to design a buckle that could be used for climbing strength applications however I am still not convinced about the safety of this. I think much of the reason you have a 22 kilonewton carabiner is that the device is subjected to more than just loading strength but also environmental factors such as abrasion and impact.  In the case of a buckle the abrasion could make it not hold the webbing as well as reducing the strength.
comments.author: ftc

comments.text: Just tested one I printed, this will make a great buckle for belts and backpack straps but it only held about 40 lbs before failing spectacularly. (If you test it I suggest safety goggles).  I can't claim my settings are the best you could make them however I don't see this getting the two orders of magnitude in strength you need before I would trust anyone's life to it.
comments.author: ftc

comments.text: First of all thankyou for doing a test on this design. I knew that it was not ultimately anywhere near up to specification, but figured I could post it as a proof of concept. I am currently working on a much beefier model that so far has not shown any strain under over 300 lbs of force.
comments.author: ftc

comments.text: A few more thoughts. Climbing stitching is very specific and something that I have not looked into but from the little I have read there are many ways you can mess up and make stitching that looks good but doesn't actually work.

title: Really simple 20x20mm extruder fan mount and nozzle thingy for a Prusa i3

description.text:
I didn't like the big fan mounts and nozzles around, so I knocked up this one to fit a tiny 20x20mm fan that I could just glue on to the extruder carriage. I print in ABS and I want the fan just for bridging and very small layers. This fan doesn't push much air, but does help avoid melt downs with small things like the hand supports and antennae on the Ultimaker robot.

The mount was glued with Shoe Goo (AKA Goop) to the bottom of the X axis carriage on my Prusa i3. Adjusted with a cardboard spacer to be about 1mm off the build plate and left overnight.

Most printed objects need sanding once they're out of the printer, but it's often tricky to get into all the shapes with raw sandpaper. I made up these sanding tools which I printed, sanded, and then glued bits of sandpaper to the shaped heads with PVA glue. The PVA holds well enough for sanding if you wrap a bit of elastic around the head while it dries, but when the sandpaper is used up, you can still peel it off and replace it.  
I intend to print a set of these out in a few different colours when I get some more filament, and match each sander to a grade of sandpaper, so I can get progressively smoother.  
For some reason, the concave head wouldn't export properly as an *.STL file, so I had to split it into a head and handle. Plastic glue holds the parts well enough that it's strong enough to sand with.  
I've included the original blender files, so you can modify these in blender if you need a customised sanding tool for a model. You may also be able to get the concave tool to print out in one piece.
Print with supports enabled, glue the concave head on with plastic cement or acetone. Fix sandpaper to the shaped heads with PVA and hold in place with elastic bands while drying.

description.text:
30-JAN-2018: NEW IMPROVED model https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2778015

Details, links for electronic components & firmware downloads are at http://bigcooter.com/?p=1584!

28-DEC-2017: ADDED Toranado 120mm Fan Grill STL file, compliments the Toranado Extruder https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1246951

20-JAN-2016: UPDATE - added sidecover with 2 terminal banana 12V Aux Power Outlet.

Build a low cost cutomizable 3D Printer Power Supply & Electronics enclosure. This is a modular design which can be configured multiple ways to utilize the plentifully low cost (<$30) 360watt power supplies used on many RepRap 3D printers. The standard 40mm high speed noisy fan has been replaced by a quiet large 120mm fan. Optionally, additional boards can be encased in this enclosure, such as: Arduino / Ramps boards, Raspberry Pi board/camera, etc.... The idea is to pick and choose the components to print, then build a customized electronics unit for a 3D printer ... with only minimal remixing and/or making of specialized board brackets. The Raspberry Pi module, enables the use of OctoPi, a fantastic OpenSource 3D printer interface with remote access and camera integration.

NOTE: Reference STL files have been included for all the purchased components, and for the BigCooter Raspberry OctoPi (in My Things at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:713389 )

Design description will be as follows:

Make from universal Power Supply (12 or 24V, 360W)
120mm cooling fan - low noise ... LED lights look great!
modular design - versatile
board mounts for Arduino / Ramps & Rasp Pi - camera
option for mounting 4-Channel 10A Relay board
option for mounting 1-Channel 30A high current relay

Additional modules are coming, and I encourage others to develop their own compatible modules to share (when doing so, please follow the design standards below).

Currently available modules and components:

USB 12V power (for Raspberry Pi and other applications)
Raspberry Pi with camera
7" LCD display
120mm silent cooling fan
RAMPS 1.4 / Arduino
120V cord outlet / on-off switch
30amp heat-bed relay (recommended for RepRap machines w/RAMPS 1.4, prevents over-heating failures / fires, OMG!!!)
Base Cooling Vent / wire router
Oversize swivel base cooling vent with adjustable wire routing
Raspberry Pi Oversize base module

  • in development - oversize modules are for use at base of unit, they provide added stability and larger electronics packaging

Suggestions for New Modules (link to here if you develop any):

Large base, for more stability
Graphical LCD display
Mount for BigCooter 7" LCD Display (see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:676916 )

The blue/black pair of units in attached photos run a large 3D printer. One unit contains Ramps1.4/Arduino and the other unit contains a 4-channel relay board for running a large headbed with 4 heating zones (4 standard size heatbeds). Both units have USB outlets for powering devices and one has a Raspberry OctoPi which uses My Thing 7" LCD display shown in the photos. This demonstrates the versatility of this Enclosure, it can be configured multiple ways! .. resulting in a clean, low noise, professional appearing system.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/aEgCTYQNRkx

PLA - black parts
ABS - colored parts

All plastic 3D printed parts have been designed to fit on most standard size print beds. The fully assembled unit approximately 12" tall x 5" wide x 4" deep.

All screws are M3 button head, with no captive nuts (thread PLA plastic using M3 tap, or "self-tap" the screw into the hole). Holes in plastic parts are intentionally undersized to improve hole quality and
size accuracy, resize holes with drill (30 to 3.3mm diameter drill for through holes, and 2.4 to 2.6mm diameter drill for M3 tap).

The included Picatinny 20mm Rails are designed to fasten to 3 sides of the 360W power supply case. This rail is the BigCooter standard mounting system, a widely used, versatile, strong system based on the original MIL spec ... almost anything you can imagine, can be mounted securely on this rail system.

description.text:
This is another variant of the original P3Steel "Leonardo" by Irobri, with a few more changes (listed below) compared to my previously published version 2.01. The main point of this version 2.5 DXL is to more easily support an optional single or dual Bowden extruder setup. Of course it can still be built with a "standard" Prusa i3 Greg's Wade 's Geared Extruder.

There are no other functional changes from version 2.01 apart from those listed below:

  • The frame now supports an optional dual Bowden extruder setup, with the two extruder steppers mounted directly on the frame's left and right side panels..
  • The frame width was increased by 10mm.
  • The frame height was increased by 10mm.
  • All frame screw holes are now the same diameter (3.2mm).
  • The electronics mount holes were raised by 10mm.

The changes are as few and as small as possible because of two reasons:

  • The design of the P3Steel and all its variants sticks to the K.I.S.S. principle.
  • We don't change something that works well.

Again I am releasing this modified design under the same license as the original.

More information including BOM and assembly guide: http://reprap.org/wiki/P3Steel

The RepRap.org wiki P3Steel pages contain a BOM and full instructions for assembling all versions of the P3Steel.

Also note that I have designed a full set of optimized printed parts to assemble the P3Steel versions 2.01 and 2.5 DXL, and have published them here on Thingiverse (see my designs).

Drafont is a font system for the OpenSCAD program to have Unicode characters from scalable TrueType fonts. Example Usage: To make the Hi! greeting at left, do as follows:
  • Download freeserif_basiclatin.scad and freeserif_cherokee.scad (see below for download links)
  • Type this into Openscad:
    • use <freeserif_basiclatin.scad>;
    use <freeserif_cherokee.scad>; d=12; // detail level - use 1 or 12
    freeserif_H(d)
    freeserif_i(d); translate([-800,-1600,0])
    freeserif_13a3(d)
    freeserif_13cf(d)
    freeserif_13f2(d); Features
  • Each character is a module. Chain them together for auto-positioning
  • Each character can be referred to by unicode, or a 'shorthand' name
  • At the top of each .scad file is a list of the characters available
  • Two detail levels: 1 and 12
  • You can generate your own .scad font from a Truetype font, with any detail level you want. Download the .py files, edit settings at the end of ddump.py, and run it as follows:
    • python ddump.py FreeSerif.ttf 0x0041-0x007a > freeserif_basiclatin.scad
    python ddump.py FreeSerif.ttf 0x13a0-0x13f4 > freeserif_cherokee.scad Bugs
  • If you use the same char twice in a word, you have to use two _ (underscore)
  • Some complicated characters won't render properly
  • It is slow
  • CJK characters in FreeSerif not working
  • Some fonts don't work, at all (Sawasdee)

comments.author: Premium

comments.text:
Si le voile est important il risque de pousser autour de l'axe Z décalant ainsi l'impression X suivant un cercle.
Le but du roulement est de limiter le mouvement indésirable de la tige filetée. Si elle était bridée sur le roulement nous risquerions de bomber la tige et de faire pire que sans roulement. Dans la mesure ou elle coulisse dans le roulement on a juste tendance à limiter ses mouvements axiaux.
Pour tester le résultat vous pouvez imprimer un petit cube aux parois verticales assez hautes et vérifier l'alignement des couches sur ses faces avec une lumière rasante.
Si vous remarquez un défaut d'alignement tous les 0,8mm c'est que vous avez un problème avec la tige fileté.

title: Bike light to rack adapter plate

description.text:
I have a rack on my bike, and a light from Planet Bike. The mounting hardware for the light allows it to mount on the seat post, but then it will be covered by anything on the rack. It can be mounted on one of the support struts for the rack, but then it is quite low, and often gets knocked out of alignment.
The ideal place to mount is on the rack itself, which has a fitting for a mini license plate.
This object is an adapter for the bike light, that bolts onto the license plate fitting, and still has a functioning quick release for the light.
The OpenSCAD file is broken out into modules, so if you have a Planet Bike light set, you can re-use the mounting bracket and release lever and make your own custom light mountings!
Print it. Use two 7/32 or M5 nuts and bolts to attach it. Might make sense to use a lock washer to secure against vibration.

I got tired of trying to get my printbed level on my Mono mendel from ReprapPro so I started watching some guides on how to enable autoleveling. It seems that the best way is to use a capacitive sensor since it will work on everything and not just metal. They are also pretty cheap on Ebay http://goo.gl/eFjuBZ so it's a win win!

You can see the X and Y offset in the image above and that should make the setup a lot easier.

So far I only tested to print it in PLA and the fitting for the sensor is really good actually, now I just need to print it in ABS!
Remember to use ABS since the hotend will be mounted on this and it will get to hot for PLA
